{{infobox winter storm |name=December 2000 nor'easter |image location=December 30, 2000 snowstorm map.jpg |image name=A [[surface weather analysis]] of the nor'easter |stormtype=winter storm |date formed=December 27, 2000 |date dissipated=December 31, 2000 |RSI=3.37 |pressure= |maximum amount= |Total damages (USD)= |total fatalities= |areas affected= }}
The '''December 2000 nor'easter''' was a significant winter storm that impacted the [[Mid-Atlantic States|Mid-Atlantic]] and [[New England]] regions of the [[United States]] around the end of the month.<ref name="report1">{{cite web|author=Tom Ross|title=Climate-Watch, December 2000|date=January 8, 2001|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/oa/climate/extremes/2000/december/extremes1200.html}}</ref> It began as an [[Alberta clipper]] that moved southeastward through the central United States and weakened over the [[Ohio Valley]]. However, it redeveloped off the coast of [[North Carolina]] and moved northward as it intensified. It moved into central [[Long Island]] and eventually tracked northward into New England. The storm dropped heavy precipitation throughout the Northeast, especially in northern [[New Jersey]] and eastern [[New York (state)|New York]], where snowfall often exceeded {{convert|2|ft|m|abbr=on}}. Even so, as it struck on a weekend, its effects were generally minor and mostly limited to travel delays, traffic accidents, and business closures.
==Synoptic history== [[File:December 2000 nor'easter snowfall map.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Snowfall accumulations from the nor'easter|alt=Map detailing total snowfall amounts from a particular storm. Light snowfall—marked in gray—extends as far south as Tennessee; the heaviest snow, indicated by two shades of blue, is concentrated over northern New Jersey, New York, and western New England.]] The storm developed as an [[Alberta clipper]]-type [[low pressure area]] that moved southeastward across the [[Great Plains]] and [[Midwest U.S.|Midwest]]. Throughout [[North Dakota]], [[Minnesota]] and [[Iowa]], moderate snowfall accompanied the system. After weakening over the [[Ohio Valley]], the storm redeveloped off the coast of [[North Carolina]]. In the days preceding the event, a cyclone over eastern Canada circulated cold air southward. Computer models indicated the potential for a major storm up to seven days in advance; however, initially, certain forecasts suggested that a separate storm over the southern U.S. would merge with the clipper. Instead, this feature moved out to sea.<ref name="Kocin1">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 629</ref>
As the secondary storm began to intensify offshore, precipitation rapidly expanded and tracked northward towards southern [[Virginia]], eastern [[Maryland]] and [[Delaware]], largely in the form of freezing rain, ice, and snow. From 0200 UTC on December 30 to 1200 UTC, the cyclone intensified by 13 [[mbar]], and continued to deepen for several more hours. Snowfall reached southern [[New Jersey]] between 0600 and 0800 UTC, and [[New York City]] at around 1000 UTC. [[Thundersnow]] developed within heavy bands in some areas.<ref name="Kocin2">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 630</ref> The significant snow was characterized by a sharp western cutoff; for example, in Chester County, accumulations ranged from around 6&nbsp;inches in the far eastern parts of the county to only an inch along its western border with Lancaster County.
While located off the [[New Jersey]] coast, the storm stopped strengthening and slowly moved northward. The center was situated near central Long Island at 2100 UTC. Across eastern [[Long Island]] and parts of eastern New England, snow mixed with and, in some cases, changed over to rain. The surface low had moved into eastern [[Connecticut]] by early on December 31.<ref name="Kocin2"/> As it continued to head northeastward, a new center of low pressure developed near [[Boston]] and moved towards coastal [[Maine]].<ref name="Kocin3">Kocin and Uccellini, p. 636</ref> The storm system had abated by January 1.<ref>{{cite web|author=NOAA Central Library Data Imaging Project|title=Monday, January 1, 2001 Daily Weather Map|date=January 1, 2001|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/dwm/2001/20010101-20010107.djvu}}</ref>
==Impact== [[File:Nor'easter_2000-12-31_weather_map.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Weather map of the nor'easter on December 31, 2000|alt=Map of the northeastern United States, showing a more tightly-wound storm. The low center is situated over northern New England, although precipitation extends well to the west.]] The storm produced moderate to heavy snowfall from eastern [[Pennsylvania]] through New Jersey, New York, and New England, extending as far north as Maine. As much as {{convert|30|in|m|abbr=on}} fell west of the New York City metropolitan region, which generally reported {{convert|10|to|16|in|m|abbr=on}} of snow, making it the biggest snowstorm at the time since the [[North American blizzard of 1996]]. [[Washington, D.C.]] and [[Baltimore]] recorded little or no snowfall, while {{convert|10|in|cm|abbr=on}} impacted Philadelphia. Eastern New York, especially the [[Hudson Valley]] and [[Catskill Mountains]], western Connecticut, western and central [[Massachusetts]], [[Vermont]], [[New Hampshire]] and Maine also picked up heavy snowfall.<ref name="report1"/><ref name="Kocin1"/><ref name="Kocin2"/> Eastern New England received up to {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=on}} before dry air from the south reduced the duration of the snow.<ref name="Kocin3"/>
About 30 flights were canceled at the [[Philadelphia International Airport]], and the city declared a snow emergency. [[Amtrak]] canceled [[Metroliner (Amtrak)|Metroliner]] service along the northeast corridor from Washington, D.C. to New York City. Numerous businesses throughout eastern Pennsylvania closed on December 30, although because the storm struck on a weekend, the number of traffic accidents was fairly low.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Pennsylvania: Heavy Snow|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~405163}}</ref>
In New Jersey, increasing winds caused blowing and drifting of the snow and led to near-blizzard conditions. Behind the storm, very cold and gusty weather lingered.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New Jersey: Heavy Snow|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~398978}}</ref> [[New Jersey Transit]] shut down bus service in northern portions of the state, and rail lines had 20-minute delays. Most injuries in the state were related to physical strain while shoveling, [[snow blower]] accidents or slips and falls. As the snowfall was of a light nature, few trees limbs and electrical wires were downed by the storm. GPU Energy reported only around 5,500 power outages. A countywide state of emergency was declared in [[Sussex County, New Jersey|Sussex County]], as vehicles were sliding off roadways. Several other traffic accidents and delays were reported throughout the state, and in [[Somerset County, New Jersey|Somerset County]], a few roads were closed due to the snow. A Red Cross shelter was opened for residents of a [[Spotswood, New Jersey|Spotswood]] trailer park.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New Jersey: Heavy Snow (2)|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~398977}}</ref>
In New York State, the heaviest snow peaked at {{convert|29|in|m|abbr=on}} in Platte Cove, [[Greene County, NY|Greene County]]. Despite 50 flight cancellations at the [[Albany International Airport]] and several traffic accidents, no major damage or injuries were reported.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for New York: Heavy Snow|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~400055 }}</ref> Although heavy snow fell in the state, no major damage was reported in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Connecticut: Heavy Snow|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~383000}}</ref> In Massachusetts and Rhode Island, high winds, gusting to as high as {{convert|50|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} buffeted the coast.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Massachusetts: Strong Wind|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~383000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Event Record Details for Rhode Island: Strong Wind|date=|publisher=National Climatic Data Center|accessdate=January 4, 2010|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~405214}}</ref>
